    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen attempting to `pipe:write({})`, `nvim` spuriously segfaults with following stacktrace:\n\n<img width=\"2326\" height=\"603\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/845b1d71-14e0-4003-b3f7-d021f69a8858\" />\n\n[backtrace.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/24093530/backtrace.txt)\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```bash\nnvim --clean --headless -u ./minimal.lua; echo $?\n```\n\n```lua\n-- ./minimal.lua\nlocal pipe = vim.uv.new_pipe()\nassert(pipe)\n\n---@diagnostic disable-next-line:missing-fields\nvim.uv.spawn(\"cat\", {\n\tstdio = {\n\t\tpipe,\n\t},\n}, function(_) end)\n\nfor _ = 1, 20, 1 do\n\tpipe:write({})\nend\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI would expect empty writes to be either silently ignored, or to return an lua error via the callback.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nTested with: `NVIM v0.11.5`, `NVIM v0.12.0-dev-1803+g78bbe53f76`\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, vim doesn't have `libuv` nor `lua` support\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux arch-book 6.17.9-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\n`alacritty` / `tmux`\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\n`xterm-256color`\n\n### Installation\n\n- build from repo\n- system package manager\n- downloaded from github releases",
